Step 1: Install LVM tools (if not installed)
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo apt update
sudo apt install lvm2 -y       # For Ubuntu/Debian
# OR for RHEL/CentOS
sudo yum install lvm2 -y
Step 2: Prepare the disk for LVM
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo pvcreate /dev/vdb
This initializes /dev/vdb as a physical volume.

Step 3: Create a volume group
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo vgcreate extstorage_vg /dev/vdb
extstorage_vg is the name of the volume group.

You can add more disks to this VG later to expand storage.

Step 4: Create a logical volume
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo lvcreate -L 50G -n extstorage_lv extstorage_vg
sudo lvcreate -l 100%FREE -n SP_lv SP_vg
50G = initial size (you can use all available space by -l 100%FREE).

extstorage_lv = logical volume name.

Step 5: Format the logical volume
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/extstorage_vg/extstorage_lv
Step 6: Mount the logical volume
bash
Copy
Edit
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/extstorage
sudo mount /dev/extstorage_vg/extstorage_lv /mnt/extstorage
Check:

bash
Copy
Edit
df -h
Step 7: Make it persistent at boot
Edit /etc/fstab:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo nano /etc/fstab
Add:

bash
Copy
Edit
/dev/extstorage_vg/extstorage_lv  /mnt/extstorage  ext4  defaults  0  2
Save and test:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo umount /mnt/extstorage
sudo mount -a
Step 8: Dynamically extend storage later
If you later add another disk /dev/vdc:

Initialize as PV:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo pvcreate /dev/vdc
Extend volume group:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo vgextend extstorage_vg /dev/vdc
Extend logical volume:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo lvextend -l +100%FREE /dev/extstorage_vg/extstorage_lv
Resize filesystem:

bash
Copy
Edit
sudo resize2fs /dev/extstorage_vg/extstorage_lv
âœ… Now your storage is bigger without losing existing data.
